06321nam a22007335i 9780822384717DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20032003ncu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808223847177 a10.1515/97808223847172doi  a(DE-B1597)554504  a(OCoLC)191222320  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ancucUS-NC 4aTR15b.P495 2003 7aPHO0100002bisacsh04a77022300aPhotography's Other Histories /ced. by Christopher Pinney, Nicolas Peterson, Nicholas Thomas. 1aDurham : bDuke University Press, c[2003] 4c©2003  a1 online resource (295 p.) :b128 halftones, 1 table  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aObjects/Histories : 1700tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: ‘‘How the Other Half . . .’’ -- t1. Personal Archives -- tRelating to Photographs -- tGrowing Up with Aborigines -- tWhen Is a Photograph Worth a Thousand Words? -- t2. Visual Economies -- tThe Making of Professional ‘‘Savages’’: From P. T. Barnum (1883) to the Sunday Times (1998) -- tNavajo and Photography -- tThe Japanese Colonial Eye: Science, Exploration, and Empire -- tThe Changing Photographic Contract: Aborigines and Image Ethics -- tSupple Bodies: The Papua New Guinea Photographs of Captain Francis R. Barton, 1899–1907 -- t3. Self-Fashioning and Vernacular Modernism -- tFigueroa Aznar and the Cusco Indigenistas: Photography and Modernism in Early-Twentieth-Century Peru -- tNotes from the Surface of the Image: Photography, Postcolonialism, and Vernacular Modernism -- tImagined Journeys: The Likoni Ferry Photographers of Mombasa, Kenya -- tYoruba Photography: How the Yoruba See Themselves -- tWorks Cited -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aMoving the critical debate about photography away from its current Euro-American center of gravity, Photography’s Other Histories breaks with the notion that photographic history is best seen as the explosion of a Western technology advanced by the work of singular individuals. This collection presents a radically different account, describing photography as a globally disseminated and locally appropriated medium. Essays firmly grounded in photographic practice—in the actual making of pictures—suggest the extraordinary diversity of nonwestern photography.Richly illustrated with over 100 images, Photography’s Other Histories explores from a variety of regional, cultural, and historical perspectives the role of photography in raising historical consciousness. It includes two first-person pieces by indigenous Australians and one by a Seminole/Muskogee/Dine' artist. Some of the essays analyze representations of colonial subjects—from the limited ways Westerners have depicted Navajos to Japanese photos recording the occupation of Manchuria to the changing "contract" between Aboriginal subjects and photographers. Other essays highlight the visionary quality of much popular photography. Case studies centered in early-twentieth-century Peru and contemporary India, Kenya, and Nigeria chronicle the diverse practices that have flourished in postcolonial societies. Photography’s Other Histories recasts popular photography around the world, as not simply reproducing culture but creating it.Contributors. Michael Aird, Heike Behrend, Jo-Anne Driessens, James Faris, Morris Low, Nicolas Peterson, Christopher Pinney, Roslyn Poignant, Deborah Poole, Stephen Sprague, Hulleah Tsinhnahjinnie, Christopher Wright  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aPhotographyxHistory. 0aPhotographyxSocial aspectsxHistory. 7aPhotography / History.2bisacsh1 aAird, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAird, Michael.1 aBehrend, Heike, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/